Kaisa Kaunonen wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; Hi,
&gt; I have never used surt scope although it looks very interesting.
&gt; 
&gt; What if I have a list of 10000 seeds with all sorts of addresses
&gt; having domains, subdomains and strange paths.
&gt; I&#39;d give the list to Heritrix which generates the initial scope surt
&gt; list from seeds. Maybe it could end up with 100 surts? or 1000

Yes -- if some of the generated SURT prefixes turn out to be
redundant. For example if you included...

   http://www.example.fi
   http://www.example.fi/archives/

... they would both be used as seeds, but for the purposes of
scoping, they would be translated into the &quot;implied&quot; SURT prefixes:

   http://(fi,example,www,
   http://(fi,example,www,)/archives/

However, every URI that would be ruled in by the second SURT
prefix would also be ruled in by the first. So the second is
discarded from the sorted SURT prefix list maintained by the
crawler for scope decisions.

&gt; How can I verify before crawling that this group of surts
&gt; presents exactly the scope I want? At least it takes a lot of time :)

Other than meticulously looking things over, the best current
strategy is to set up and launch a test crawl with the relevant
scope/seed settings, and then examine the dumped SURT prefixes
actually in use, and crawl logs, to see if they match expected
behavior.

We&#39;ve also taken Andy&#39;s suggestion, and it will now be possible
to specify SURT prefixes -- either exactly, or as implied by
a regular URI -- in the &#39;seeds&#39; file/input-box.

So, when using SurtPrefixScope, any line beginning &#39;+&#39; is considered
a scoping directive. It can be either a literal SURT prefix (if it
looks SURT-like), or a plain URI/hostname to be converted to the
implied SURT prefix.

So,

   http://www.example.fi
   +http://(fi,

...would take the HTTP URI as a seed, but then consider everything
discovered in the &#39;.fi&#39; domain as in scope -- that is, it&#39;s matched
by the given SURT prefix.

&gt; It would be nice if there still was the old domain/host scope 
&gt; available. Using it would be like saying &#39;don&#39;t do any calculations
&gt; of your own, just simply crawl these&#39;

They won&#39;t go away anytime soon... I think they&#39;ll stay until we&#39;re
confident we have a better way to specify simple crawls.

- Gordon @ IA

